So if anyone else has any tips for managing #ActuallyAutistic #AutisticBurnout drop them below. I hope this helps someone. I’m definitely FEELING the progress, so I feel quite hopeful. Sometimes I still have days where I just rest becuase I have no extra energy. But it’s working.

(9 cont…) cleaning and organizing my space, strictly to make it as functional as possible. So trash out first, then functional things I need like clothes, medication easily accessible, food accessible, etc. and I slowly feel it working.

9 and currently the final tip) working on my long neglected home. Cleaning, trash out, putting stuff away, etc. things are a wreck and I function worse when they are. I took about a week to rest after cutting social stuff, and then have spent any left over energy…

(8 cont) so this looks like buying microwaveable pouches of barilla pasta, velvets cheese sauce packets or ragu spaghetti sauce packets, and making it in under 2min. Oh and using paper plates/bowls as needed. No shame right now, just function and surviving.

8) making things that I need to survive daily be as convenient as possible within my means. Eating out every night isn’t within my means. But pasta is my main safe food and I don’t have the spoons to boil water and make if. As easy as it may be normally, it’s not right now.

(7 cont…) also explaining my low tolerance for auditory stimuli has looked like “Mama’s ears hurt right now so we have to be a little quieter”. And his hugs have been in the form of a “tight squeeze” forward facing chest to chest. It’s the only way that’s not too much atm

7) setting boundaries with my toddler. I’m thankful we taught him consent from an early age so for the most part he always asks if he can have a hug or hug us, but I’ve also had to find ways to explain that I’m touched out, or that I have to hug him a certain way for me to be ok

6) no trying new foods or new games or anything. Nothing new. Also nothing that is a “sometimes” food or activity. (Like sometimes I can handle the texture of a food but sometimes it’s overwhelming), because chances are I can’t handle it during #AutisticBurnout
5) calming sounds in my headset. Usually rain playlists I’ve mail, but lately it’s been a 1hr long “Skyrim rainy day” or “Skyrim tavern” ambience video on YT. They are my comfort ambience

4) after cutting social interactions, I rested. A lot. I went to bed early for about a week, and slept in/took naps on the weekend. When I didn’t sleep, I spent time coloring in my coloring books. Low stress and an activity where I could be mindful

(3 cont) so I let everyone what I was doing, and I deleted most social media from my phone that caused stress chemicals to flood my system. Twitter is all I have left becuase I use it for news but I cap myself at 10min per day, and usually don’t look at replies if I’m overwhelmed

3) I cut all direct 1-to-1 non essential social interactions and anywhere where I’m required to mask if possible. I love my friends and family deeply, but I realized I couldn’t make any progress continuing the way I was

2) I finally got me a function pair of sunglasses. It’s getting warm outside and I drive to work everyday (20min round commute), plus I drive throughout the day for work. The bright sun often gives my headaches and adds to overwhelming sensory input. Sunglasses are a must
(Cont. from 1) I wear them literally whenever possible. It helps cut down on any added sound and sensory input and allows me to be functional. When I can’t, I’ve been using loop ear plugs

1) first and foremost - my pair of noise cancelling Bluetooth headphones had broken, and I never replaced them. I finally got new ones. Not everyone can afford that I realize, but best $60 I’ve spent on my health and well-being

Ya’ll I’ve been slowly (very slowly) working through my home, cleaning and organizing a very neglected space (all of it). #AutisticBurnout has had me BAD since November, but I’m making do. But since I seem to be on the uptick, I’ll share what has helped so far #ActuallyAutistic

At least having it documented in a central location would save me having to do it over and over again lol.

This is even when I ASK whether they want advice or just to vent. They almost always want advice because they know I’ve been there. So I do all this labor and it feels like it’s not appreciated even by well meaning people.
Especially when I cite dozens or sources and link to tons of resources for things only for that person to be like “yeah. That sounds like it makes sense. I think I’m just gonna hope it goes away”.

I just wish there was a way I could get my knowledge out into the world in a documented way, and I could link it to people who need it. Partially becuase I’m exhausted and the mental work to rehash the same advice with different people over and over is overwhelming.

Not to mention being a parent before I was ready, and not having the ability to not work full time while in school, and also dealing with adhd and autism and everything that brings while having a toddler at home and working full time 😵‍💫
But again the issue lies in I hold no degrees or “real” credentials in anything. Mostly becuase I’ve never been able to commit myself to any single path for college or a career.

I’ve thought of writing a book and compiling all my super practical knowledge in one place, especially for young people. Because the people who most often I find would benefit from it are other millennials or Gen Z.

Most of my life I’ve had to teach myself everything. I’ve suffered the consequences of not knowing things. I’ve dealt with the wrong decisions I’ve made from lack of knowledge. And I always vow to learn from it.

I’ve had people in my life that were supposed to support me in one way or another turn on me and leave me out to dry at every.single.turn. Parents, teachers, mentors, doctors, friends, family, bosses, coworkers, professors, advisors, therapists, you name it.
I’ve been told by people who realize I’m usually right on practical shit that I have wisdom that greatly exceeds my age of just 29, and it’s becuase I’ve been through a lot of fucking trauma.

OR it’s like “it’s actually not best for building credit to pay off a loan you take out all in one lump sum because you get more positive credit when you show you can make payments over time, typically for at least a year”

For the record: it’s never serious shit. It’s like, “hey if you’re feeling nauseous something that can really help is those little starlight mints. They are like $1 at Walgreens and have real peppermint oil in them which cha help with nausea” & they act like I’ve grown two heads

And every.single.time that person will come back to me and say something along the lines of “wow you were actually right and I wish I would have just done that”. But that same person will do it again with something else.
It’s incredibly insulting considering I ALWAYS admit when I flat out don’t know something, or even if I’m not sure or don’t fully understand. But no, when I’m certain I’m certain.

And I wish I had a way of sharing my knowledge with more people. Most well meaning people in my life (friends, family, etc) will ignore advice they come to me for because they just, idk, assume I don’t know what I’m talking about, and will directly ask if it’s just “a feeling”
It’s not just medical though. It’s financial, social/interpersonal, technical, medical, and various other types of advice.

Most of this has been practical health advice due to having to navigate a shitty medical system and find things that work outside of direct medical professional advise, but then later backed up by a doctor who listened to me.

But because I hold no degree, job title, etc, my advice and thoughts are never taken seriously by most even well meaning people in my life, despite them knowing the extensive amount of knowledge and time and work I’ve put into it all

Most of my knowledge is very practical and evidence based, and I can cite all sorts of research and evidence to back up things, and often have the validation of experts in my life on the things I’m taking about (like my doctors, for instance)
Know what sucks about being a Jack of all trades type of person? I have a TON of knowledge about a lot of different things, but I hold no real credentials for what society accepts as valid. 🧵

@cycnet The abuse suffered has way more to do with the person who experienced it than it does with whoever/whatever caused it.

@cycnet Here another example: If a parent ends up homeless and can't feed their kid and their kid starves, does it make the parent a bad person? No. Does the child still suffer abuse from it? Yes. Does that make the parent an abuser? No. Should we just give them food and shelter? Yes.

@cycnet And absolutely a better solution is to figure out the root cause of the abuse and fix that otherwise no one heals. But the behaviors, even if symptoms of something bigger, can still be abusive.
@cycnet But child neglect, intended or not, one time off or not, a symptom of something bigger or not, IS child abuse.

@cycnet My parents didn’t neglect me. They were deliberately abusive in a lot if not most of the abuse they caused. I’m giving other separate abuse examples. Neglect is abuse; whether it’s intended or not. A parent can learn and grow and a child can be placed back with the parent (1/2)

@cycnet Taking choice for someone from the matter makes it abusive. Telling someone they would have to stay in that scenario because the disabled person doesn’t mean it, makes them subject to abuse because they don’t have a choice in the manner on pain they are experiencing.

@cycnet even if they didn’t mean to and it was due to a disability. But the OP implied that If me, in this scenario, didn’t want to be around that person, it would be ableist of me because you wouldn’t be able to help stepping on my toe. And it’s not. (One more reply coming)

@cycnet And in like that, like if you were blind and there was nothing you could do to prevent it, then it would be up to me to decide whether or not I wanted to set a boundary for myself. It wouldn’t be ableist for me not to hang out with someone who constantly stepped on my toe, (1/2)

@cycnet Yes but if you continue to step on my toe, knowing that you often do it, but just simply don’t take extra steps to try not to, then it becomes abusive. You’re not *meaning* to, but you’re just also not taking extra steps to prevent the behavior. Context and nuance is important.
@cycnet But the idea that you have to have any kind of malice or intent behind abuse for it to be abuse is also harmful and can minimize true abuse people have gone through.

@cycnet As an adult now, I understand the difference and how majority of people mental health or other neurodivergent conditions, are not abusers. We are far more likely to be the victims of abuse. And like I said I don’t like labeling any behavior as a whole as abuse…

@cycnet …suffered. Just because it wasn’t intentional, and was partly due to symptoms of their untreated conditions, doesn’t mean it wasn’t abuse. But I don’t blame their conditions. I don’t blame people who have those conditions. I blame them as individuals, because

@cycnet Are direct results of them not being managed properly and me seeing that after I left home and they got help. I was constantly told by people my parents did their best and loved me the best they could because they were sick, and trying to minimize the abuse my brother and I…

@cycnet The easiest examples I can think to go back to are parents with untreated mental health disordered because it’s what I went through first hand. Both of my parents needed mental health treatment but didn’t even think anything was wrong with them. So much of their behavior…

@cycnet I’m also not advocating for just labeling any behavior as a whole as abusive. I think context and nuance is extremely important. But things they are symptoms of someone’s mental health, especially when it’s not treated properly, can absolutely be abusive

@cycnet Telling someone, anyone, who’s a victim of abuse that it’s not abuse because even some of what they went through were symptoms of someone’s mental health that may or may not have been treated is a form of minimizing victims and not believing them.

@cycnet But at that point it’s not about the person who is “committing” the behavior. The behavior itself can be abusive without the person doing the behavior being an abuser. That, I feel, is the difference between it. (This is gonna new a couple replies)

I do this every time I read. And it’s like once I do a specific one enough I catalog it away in my brain for a similar circumstance irl to use it if I need it. I didn’t realize exactly what I’ve been doing though. #ActuallyAutistic

…I never want to go through it, I hate it. I literally couldn’t function, form words, and struggled just processing my own thoughts. I NEED to learn to unmask as much as possible to prevent this from happening. #actuallyAutistic #autisticburnout #burnout #Neurodivergent

After not masking all evening (because I physically couldn’t), and not helping, I feel like I’m starting to be able to process stuff again, like I have room in my brain for everything outside of me. Holy fuck if this is even a mild and short experience with autistic burn out…

He pointed it out tonight that this was probably a form of nonverbal related to me being autistic and I had never thought of it. I didn’t even come into realizing I was autistic until the last 1.5-2yr. And I’m still learning so much about myself.

My partner was also concerned when I just wouldn’t talk, and would only answer by shaking my head yes or no. Once he realized this was the case he helped adapt for the evening with our toddler too (who’s also overstimulating af).

By the afternoon I had coworkers worried about me because I “wasn’t expressive at all” when I would talk, and I would speak very plainly with little inflection, because I just physically could not force myself to add any extra “flair” to my speech and conversation.

It progressively got more difficult to mask, and really this has been building for the last couple weeks (well months with work), and I feel like I’m reaching what many people talk about with autistic burn out, now that I know what this all is.

Had a very overstimulating day today and my functioning decreased over the day as I had to keep masking through it. I never realized until now that what I went through is attributed to me being autistic, including ending the night non-verbal. (THREAD) #ActuallyAutistic
